Here I digress into more of a DBC-specific question, recognizing that 
this is not a DBC mailing list...

javainsel wrote:
&gt; Consider the examples at the JUnit site:
&gt; 
&gt;     Collection collection = new ArrayList();
&gt;     collection.add(&quot;itemA&quot;);
&gt;     assertEquals(1, collection.size());
&gt;     collection.add(&quot;itemB&quot;);
&gt;     assertEquals(2, collection.size());
&gt;     
&gt; As a postcondition it would maybe look like &quot;AFTER:size() == 
&gt; BEFORE:size()++&quot; (pseudo code). This is very readable, natural and 
&gt; of much greater use for testing and documenting than JUnit/TDD.

This &quot;Contract&quot; is actually not complete.  Nor is the JUnit test. 
Neither shows the expectation of what should happen when you re-add an 
equal entry.  I know how I&#39;d do it with JUnit:

     String entry = &quot;itemA&quot;;
     collection.add(entry);
     assertEquals(1, collection.size());
     collection.add(entry);
     assertEquals(1, collection.size());
     collection.add(new String(entry));
     assertEquals(1, collection.size());

How would you capture that in a contract without re-implementing the 
method itself?  Something like this, I guess?

if ( collection.contains(obj) ) AFTER:size() == BEFORE.size()
else AFTER.size() == BEFORE.size()++;

Its just that I&#39;m now starting to rewrite what&#39;s in the method itself as 
part of the contract definition.  Hence it seems that I&#39;m dangerously 
close to code duplication for one method.

NOTE: This isn&#39;t meant to question the value of DBC; I like what DBC 
seems to offer.  I just don&#39;t see how to write useable post-conditions 
for non-trivial methods.  And this case (Collection.add(Object)) is 
actually a fairly trivial method.

